    <section id="sect-00002">
    <title>Nitriles, <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>RC≡N</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math></title>
    <para id="para-00005">Compounds containing the <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>–C≡N</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math> functional group are called <term id="term-00002">nitriles</term> and can undergo some chemistry similar to that of carboxylic acids. Simple open-chain nitriles are named by adding -<emphasis effect="italics">nitrile</emphasis> as a suffix to the alkane name, with the nitrile carbon numbered C1.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
    <media alt="The structure of 4-methylpentanenitrile. C 1 belongs to the C N group. A methyl group is attached to C 4. All the carbon atoms are numbered.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_20_01_005.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00006">Nitriles can also be named as derivatives of carboxylic acids by replacing the -<emphasis effect="italics">ic acid</emphasis> or -<emphasis effect="italics">oic acid</emphasis> ending with -<emphasis effect="italics">onitrile,</emphasis> or by replacing the -<emphasis effect="italics">carboxylic acid</emphasis> ending with -<emphasis effect="italics">carbonitrile.</emphasis> The nitrile carbon atom is attached to C1 but is not itself numbered.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00004">
    <media alt="The structures of acetonitrile (from acetic acid), benzonitrile (from benzoic acid), and 2,2-dimethylcyclohexanecarbonitrile (from 2,2-dimethylcyclohexane-carboxylic acid).">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_20_01_006.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00007">If another carboxylic acid derivative is present in the same molecule, the prefix <emphasis effect="italics">cyano</emphasis>- is used for the <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>C≡N</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math> group.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
    <media alt="The structure of methyl-4-cyanopentanoate. Cyano group is attached to C 4. The C 1 is double-bonded to an O atom and single-bonded to the O C H 3 group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_20_01_007.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
